result.execSummary:
The defendant James I. Montroy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. James I. Montroy is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • James I. Montroy was found guilty of Possession of Methamphetamine [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).
  • James I. Montroy was found guilty of Possession of Cocaine/Coca [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(c).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:41 pm 
Defendant James I. Montroy in court with attorney Jens Hubert Loberg.  Rory Eoin O'Sullivan appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  OSullivan:  Plead to Cts 1 and 2  dismiss Ct 3 - recommend 30 days jail.  No probation necessary.  Loberg agrees.  Def agrees.  Def is 43 years old with college degree in Business Administration.  Def will plead guilty to Cts 1 Poss of Meth and Ct 2 Poss of Cocaine PTAC.  Meds help him to focus.  Constitutional rights explained to defendant  Exam'd re: understanding of law, penalty and rights.  Def pleads guilty to Ct 1 Poss of Meth PTAC.  Def pleads guilty to Ct 2 Poss Cocaine PTAC.  Loberg stip to the facts in the complaint.    COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS  The court finds the defendant guilty and adjudicates defendant guilty of Ct 1 and Ct 2  -  Ct 3 is DISMISSED.   OSullivan asks for 30 days in PCJ.  Def wants to commence inpatient treatment next week.  He is on a PO hold pending completion.  30 days Jail to start today.  Huber for treatment.  Loberg responds.  Treatment is in Flambeau.  Sentence starts today and runs conc to PO hold.  Def addresses the Court.  Court orders: 30 days jail PCJ, each count concurrent, with good time, on PO hold, may be released for treatment.  Conc to Pepin Co case probation hold
